Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

1.1 Data quality issues - inaccurate datatype¶

  • "start_time" and "end_time" should be "datetime"
  • "start_station_id" should be "int"
  • "user_type" and "member_gender" should be "categorical"
  • "member_birth_year" should be "int"

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Distribution of "duration_sec" is heavily left-skwed, I performed the log-transformation to make the points more normally distributed.

Becase the dataset comes from Feburary fordgobike results, "Monthy usage" only has Feburary result.

As expected, in "daily usage", more bikes are used in weekdays. While for the "Hourly usage", 8 am and 5 pm have relatively high usage.

For "age" distribution, there are lots of outliers bigger than 60 years old. But after log transformation, it is more easily to identify most ages are around 25 - 40 years old.

For "user type", more than 90% users are subscribers.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Most of the variables need some operations to make them suitable for the next-stage analysis. Such as log transformation, or extracting "month", "day" and "hour" information from "start-time" variable.

  • The average usage time is higher in customer than subscriber, almost two times. It it a little bit weird, but as the average value can be affected by outliers, I need to take a closer look at the distribution.
In [159]:
customer = df.query('user_type == "Customer"')
subscriber = df.query('user_type == "Subscriber"')
bins = np.arange(0, 10000, 50)
plt.hist(customer['duration_sec'], alpha = 0.5, bins= bins)
plt.hist(subscriber['duration_sec'], alpha = 0.5, bins = bins)
plt.xlabel('duration_sec')
plt.title('Usage time distribution by user type')
plt.legend(labels = ['customer', 'subscriber']);
  • From above histogram, we know the distribution in customer is more spread than the subscriber, so the average time usage can be higher in customer group given lots of outliers.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

In average, customer has higher usage time compared with subscriber. But the usage time distribution of the customer is more spread which may explain why its average time is higher.

Users age between 25 - 40 have higher usage times.

In both "customer" and "subscriber" groups, their usage tendency is similar, which is higher usage in weekdays and in rush hours (8 am and 5 pm).

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Top 10 start stations are not same in "customer" and "subscriber" groups.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Based on the heatmap, we can clearly see that both "customer" and "suscriber" have relatively high bike usage in weekdays and in rush hours (8am and 5pm).

But surprisingly, in average, "customer" type has higher usage time.

Both in "customer" and "subsriber" group, the average usage time is higher in weekends.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

3 am has the highest average usage time in both two groups.
